# Sentinel Dialer — Product Rules

## Rule 1: Protect the main product boundary

Sentinel is the system of action. The dialer is the conversation runtime.
Do not move durable CRM truth into the dialer.
Do not make the dialer the real daily workspace.

## Rule 2: No raw AI writeback

Never write raw transcripts, long model dumps, or unstable inferred text directly into CRM-visible fields.
All dialer writeback must pass through typed, minimal, reviewable contracts.

## Rule 3: Optimize for founder-hour leverage

Every feature must justify itself by improving contracts per founder-hour, speed-to-lead, follow-up reliability, trust, or support-labor compression.
If not, cut or defer it.

## Rule 4: Voice first, not science project first

Prioritize: missed-call recovery, inbound answering, routing, callback booking, warm transfer, post-call summary, objection tagging, QA.
Do not prioritize autonomous cold AI calling.

## Rule 5: Every AI workflow must be traceable

All AI-assisted voice workflows must have: run ID, prompt version, trace/event log, fallback reason, and approval/review state where relevant.
No durable writeback from untraced runs.

## Rule 6: Trust-heavy moments stay human

Avoid automating negotiation, empathy-heavy inherited/family conversations, unsupported family or authority claims, and aggressive or creepy personalization.
Logan remains the closer.

## Rule 7: Prefer modular connectors

Design around replaceable providers for: voice, transcription, model layer, routing logic, summary generation, SMS/callback actions.
Avoid hard-coding assumptions that block provider swap later.

## Rule 8: Keep Lead Detail clean

Lead Detail is the primary working surface.
Anything surfaced there must improve fast comprehension, next action clarity, call readiness, or follow-up discipline.
